actions.comment:
Thanks for flagging this. Both `SKGLView` and `SKCanvasView` in the Blazor package use a non-virtual `Dispose()`, which does prevent subclasses from extending cleanup.

As a workaround, you can hide the base `Dispose` using the `new` keyword:

```csharp
public new void Dispose()
{
    // Your custom cleanup
    MyResource?.Dispose();
    // Call base disposal
    base.Dispose();
}
```

Note that this won't work polymorphically (callers holding an `SKGLView` reference will call the base `Dispose`), so it's only reliable when the subclass type is known at the call site.

The proper fix would be adopting the standard `Dispose(bool)` pattern with a `protected virtual Dispose(bool disposing)` method. We'll look into implementing this for both Blazor views.
